track_notes: I was not quite as brave as K9PM with my 4WD so I parked a bit lower and hiked a bit further.  The first 1.5 miles of my track is on rough, steep 4wd road.  There is a trail for most of the way to the summit but it is faint and at times disappears entirely.  You need to circle around a large rock formation prior to heading to the summit, and during this part of the hike the trail is thin and runs along the side of steep hill - a fall could be very bad on this section.  Summit is nice and broad with trees.
track_title: Bob Thompson Peak from Ash Canyon Rd

track_notes: Turn off Hwy 92 onto Ash Canyon Rd. Park at GPS 31.37292,-110.25982 near a Forest Service sign. If you have a 4WD high ground clearance vehicle, you may be able to drive another 0.7 mile beyond this point, up the steep rocky road to a locked FS gate at GPS 31.386264,-110.240922 where there is a parking area. If not, hike up the road to the locked gate and continue on the road beyond the gate. The road climbs higher through a series of switchbacks until it ends at a saddle. From the saddle, turn left on a path. Just above the saddle there is a fork in the path. This track follows the left fork, while my DESCENT track follows the other fork coming down from the summit. I lost the trail on the ascent and this track will lead through a bit of bushwhacking through grass. The summit offers ample room to set up several stations. The views are spectacular and one can see the US-Mexico border immediately to the south. There are many signs of migrant foot traffic, most notably, plastic bottles.
track_title: BOB THOMPSON PEAK ASCENT FROM ASH CANYON

track_notes: This track follows my descent from Bob Thompson Peak. I was able to stay on the trail the entire time, although it is easy to lose the trail due to terrain. The return route was easier to follow because I could see the trail ahead much of the time. It is much harder to see the trail ahead when ascending.
